that we've talked about before
Reveri, R-E-V-E-R-I.com.

01:39:16.840 --> 01:39:20.500
There's a great app for
accessing deep rest states

01:39:20.500 --> 01:39:24.060
or the physiological side
to try and get your system

01:39:24.060 --> 01:39:27.120
to calm down after training.

01:39:27.120 --> 01:39:30.780
There are also tools that one
can use to reduce inflammation

01:39:30.780 --> 01:39:33.720
at a kind of foundational
level away from training.

01:39:33.720 --> 01:39:35.610
And these are tools that I've talked

01:39:35.610 --> 01:39:39.560
about many times before, but
I'll just restate them again.

01:39:39.560 --> 01:39:42.160
The kind of Golden Three
according to Andy Galpin

01:39:42.160 --> 01:39:43.870
and the ones that he recommends are

01:39:43.870 --> 01:39:46.520
sufficient omega-3s again,
that can be accomplished

01:39:46.520 --> 01:39:48.590
through diet, through whole food intake

01:39:48.590 --> 01:39:50.390
or through supplementation or both.

01:39:50.390 --> 01:39:52.890
So in general, getting
above a 1,000 milligrams

01:39:52.890 --> 01:39:57.610
of EPA per day to keep
inflammation low or relatively low.

01:39:57.610 --> 01:40:01.970
Vitamin D and in some
cases, magnesium malate.

01:40:01.970 --> 01:40:04.350
Magnesium malate seems to
be particularly effective

01:40:04.350 --> 01:40:07.630
in offsetting delayed
onset muscle soreness.

01:40:07.630 --> 01:40:10.090
Soreness itself is not required

01:40:10.090 --> 01:40:13.890
for improvements in strength,
improvements in explosiveness,

01:40:13.890 --> 01:40:15.710
improvements in hypertrophy.

01:40:15.710 --> 01:40:16.543
That's a myth.

01:40:16.543 --> 01:40:19.290
Now, if you do experience
delayed onset muscle soreness,

01:40:19.290 --> 01:40:23.300
chances are you stressed that
particular muscle pretty well

01:40:23.300 --> 01:40:26.290
or even maybe to well, maybe
you stressed it too much

01:40:26.290 --> 01:40:28.460
and you need longer recovery.

01:40:28.460 --> 01:40:30.960
There's a total debate
out there about whether

01:40:30.960 --> 01:40:33.410
or not you should train again
when a muscle is still sore.

01:40:33.410 --> 01:40:34.940
I think the general takeaway is, no

01:40:34.940 --> 01:40:36.210
that means it's not recovered.

01:40:36.210 --> 01:40:38.710
And there are things
of course like massage,

01:40:38.710 --> 01:40:41.080
like fascial release
and things of that sort

01:40:41.080 --> 01:40:46.080
sauna, cold that can perhaps
accelerate the movement

01:40:47.120 --> 01:40:49.400
from soreness to not sore.

01:40:49.400 --> 01:40:51.660
But in general, the omega-3, vitamin D,

01:40:51.660 --> 01:40:55.850
and magnesium malate trio
seemed to be an effective way

01:40:55.850 --> 01:40:58.530
to reduce inflammation at
kind of a systemic level.

01:40:58.530 --> 01:41:00.520
But remember you want
inflammation provided

01:41:00.520 --> 01:41:01.890
you're not damaging the muscles so much

01:41:01.890 --> 01:41:04.200
that you're injured during
the training session

01:41:04.200 --> 01:41:08.350
because that's the stimulus
for change in those muscles.

01:41:08.350 --> 01:41:10.250
I want to talk about a few other things

01:41:10.250 --> 01:41:13.195
that support the process of
nerve to muscle communication

01:41:13.195 --> 01:41:15.850
and touch on some of the things that a lot

01:41:15.850 --> 01:41:19.230
of people are doing to try
to "enhance their workouts"

01:41:19.230 --> 01:41:20.820
and evaluate whether or not those are

01:41:20.820 --> 01:41:23.480
in fact enhancing workouts or not.

01:41:23.480 --> 01:41:26.970
Because weight training,
unlike a lot of other forms

01:41:26.970 --> 01:41:30.950
of exercise has a unique aspect to it,

01:41:30.950 --> 01:41:33.330
which is this feature
that I guess some people

01:41:33.330 --> 01:41:35.720
call it the pump which is
the fact that blood goes

01:41:35.720 --> 01:41:38.350
into the muscle when you
train, it's the only gun

01:41:38.350 --> 01:41:40.010
of training where you
actually get a window

01:41:40.010 --> 01:41:42.760
into what the result
might actually look like

01:41:42.760 --> 01:41:44.560
before you actually
accomplish that result.

01:41:44.560 --> 01:41:46.560
So if you think about when
you go out for a hard run

01:41:46.560 --> 01:41:49.270
and let's say you go
out for a two mile run,

01:41:49.270 --> 01:41:50.970
let's say your goal is to break

01:41:50.970 --> 01:41:52.500
you want to do a sub ten two mile.

01:41:52.500 --> 01:41:54.750
Actually, when I went to university

01:41:54.750 --> 01:41:57.940
I was running cross country,
my senior year of high school

01:41:57.940 --> 01:42:01.430
and I wanted to walk on
for the cross country team.

01:42:01.430 --> 01:42:03.760
And so I went out there and turned out

01:42:03.760 --> 01:42:06.430
you had to do a sub 10, two mile.

01:42:06.430 --> 01:42:09.410
And I think the best mile
I ever ran in high school

01:42:09.410 --> 01:42:11.350
