01:55:53.550 --> 01:55:55.670
There's one more thing
that I'd like to cover

01:55:55.670 --> 01:55:56.810
which is the relationship

01:55:56.810 --> 01:55:58.900
between particular kinds of exercise

01:55:58.900 --> 01:56:02.653
and our ability to think and
perform cognitive functions.

01:56:03.700 --> 01:56:06.720
We all hear that exercise
is so vital for our brain

01:56:06.720 --> 01:56:08.670
that it supports our brain
health and our body health.

01:56:08.670 --> 01:56:12.440
And indeed that's true
provided it's done correctly.

01:56:12.440 --> 01:56:16.060
However, many of us are
familiar with the experience

01:56:16.060 --> 01:56:18.260
of going for a run or going for a swim

01:56:18.260 --> 01:56:20.158
or working out hard in
the gym, and then not

01:56:20.158 --> 01:56:23.180
being able to use our brain
to be essentially useless

01:56:23.180 --> 01:56:26.260
for cognitive functions
for the rest of the day.

01:56:26.260 --> 01:56:29.440
I discussed this with
Dr. Galpin this morning,

01:56:29.440 --> 01:56:30.810
and I learned something very interesting,

01:56:30.810 --> 01:56:33.750
which is that hard bouts of exercise

01:56:33.750 --> 01:56:35.780
of the sort where you're
training near failure

01:56:35.780 --> 01:56:39.570
or you're generating focused
muscular contractions,

01:56:39.570 --> 01:56:42.120
for obsession that lasts anywhere

01:56:42.120 --> 01:56:45.000
from, I don't know, 30, 45
minutes, maybe 60 minutes

01:56:45.000 --> 01:56:46.900
or a long run where you're engaging

01:56:46.900 --> 01:56:49.570
in some interval training during that run,

01:56:49.570 --> 01:56:53.570
after exercise, there's a
reduction in oxygenation

01:56:53.570 --> 01:56:54.403
of the brain.

01:56:54.403 --> 01:56:56.760
So there's actually a quite
significant dip in the amount

01:56:56.760 --> 01:56:58.096
of oxygen that your neurons are getting

01:56:58.096 --> 01:57:00.460
and therefore your ability to think.

01:57:00.460 --> 01:57:02.795
So it's important that
you control the intensity

01:57:02.795 --> 01:57:04.894
and the duration of your
training sessions so

01:57:04.894 --> 01:57:07.650
that you're still able to do well in life

01:57:07.650 --> 01:57:09.910
and lean to life the way you need to,

01:57:09.910 --> 01:57:12.190
because I'm guessing most of you are not

01:57:12.190 --> 01:57:14.380
in a position to just prioritize
your physical training

01:57:14.380 --> 01:57:16.780
you also need to use your minds.

01:57:16.780 --> 01:57:19.100
I'm certainly familiar with
wanting to get exercise

01:57:19.100 --> 01:57:20.480
but also the requirement of needing

01:57:20.480 --> 01:57:23.623
to perform cognitive
work throughout the day.

01:57:24.640 --> 01:57:26.810
It also turns out that you can leverage

01:57:26.810 --> 01:57:29.220
something interesting
about exercise and nerve

01:57:29.220 --> 01:57:31.990
to muscle work in ways that can benefit

01:57:31.990 --> 01:57:33.950
cognitive function and focus.

01:57:33.950 --> 01:57:36.330
And it has to do with
the way that your body

01:57:36.330 --> 01:57:38.580
and your nervous system predict bouts

01:57:38.580 --> 01:57:40.360
of intense focused effort.

01:57:40.360 --> 01:57:42.660
So let's say you're doing
resistance training two

01:57:42.660 --> 01:57:44.800
or three times a week,
maybe even four times a week

01:57:44.800 --> 01:57:47.293
and you're doing it
consistently at a given time.

01:57:48.770 --> 01:57:51.830
There are clocks,
literally biological clocks

01:57:51.830 --> 01:57:54.040
within the liver and within the brain

01:57:54.040 --> 01:57:57.973
that learn to predict that
focus and that intense work.

01:57:59.130 --> 01:58:02.843
If you are trying to get
intense cognitive work done,

01:58:03.810 --> 01:58:06.470
you might try scheduling
that cognitive work

01:58:06.470 --> 01:58:09.340
on the days when you
don't do physical training

01:58:09.340 --> 01:58:11.630
at the same time when
you normally would do

01:58:11.630 --> 01:58:14.740
that intense, focused physical training.

01:58:14.740 --> 01:58:16.560
Because the systems of the body

01:58:16.560 --> 01:58:18.170
that generate acetylcholine release

01:58:18.170 --> 01:58:20.130
and other neuromodulators, the systems,

01:58:20.130 --> 01:58:22.713
of the body and brain that
generate focused effort,

01:58:23.580 --> 01:58:26.230
those are on this sort of clock mechanism

01:58:26.230 --> 01:58:28.800
in a way that you likely will find

01:58:28.800 --> 01:58:31.160
that after just a week of
training at regular times

01:58:31.160 --> 01:58:34.780
you will be able to focus
readily on other things

01:58:34.780 --> 01:58:36.840
when you're not training
provided you do it

01:58:36.840 --> 01:58:38.679
during the period of time of day

01:58:38.679 --> 01:58:40.910
when you normally would train.

01:58:40.910 --> 01:58:43.440
So is kind of an indirect positive effect.

01:58:43.440 --> 01:58:46.400
You're harnessing the focus
and the expectation of focus

01:58:46.400 --> 01:58:48.950
in your nervous system for
that particular time of day.

01:58:48.950 --> 01:58:50.740
And of course, we'd be remiss

01:58:50.740 --> 01:58:53.210
if we didn't talk about
time of day for training.

01:58:53.210 --> 01:58:56.810
It turns out that whether or
not you train in the morning

01:58:56.810 --> 01:58:59.460
or in the afternoon, it
doesn't really seem to matter

01:58:59.460 --> 01:59:02.790
for sake of things like hypertrophy
and strength, et cetera.

01:59:02.790 --> 01:59:04.210
Everyone seems to have a time of day

01:59:04.210 --> 01:59:06.020
that they prefer to train.

01:59:06.020 --> 01:59:07.820
I've said before and their reasons

01:59:07.820 --> 01:59:10.460
based on body temperature rhythms

01:59:10.460 --> 01:59:14.790
and cortisol release
that training 30 minutes,

01:59:14.790 --> 01:59:17.940
three hours or 11 hours
after your normal waking time

01:59:17.940 --> 01:59:20.040
can be very beneficial and can provide

01:59:20.040 --> 01:59:21.890
a sort of predictability or regularity

01:59:21.890 --> 01:59:25.300
to when your body will be ready to train

01:59:25.300 --> 01:59:27.840
and best apt to train well.

01:59:27.840 --> 01:59:29.040
There is some evidence that training

01:59:29.040 --> 01:59:31.450
in the afternoon is
better for performance,

01:59:31.450 --> 01:59:33.363
whereas training for
body composition changes

01:59:33.363 --> 01:59:35.640
and strain changes, et cetera

01:59:35.640 --> 01:59:37.160
doesn't really matter when you train.

01:59:37.160 --> 01:59:38.910
So you also want to make
it compatible with sleep,

01:59:38.910 --> 01:59:40.580
compatible with work that really gets

01:59:40.580 --> 01:59:42.600
down into the wits of optimization.

01:59:42.600 --> 01:59:44.130
But I think it's interesting to note

01:59:44.130 --> 01:59:47.180
that if you're going to
train at a regular time,

01:59:47.180 --> 01:59:50.260
you can take the days when you don't train

01:59:50.260 --> 01:59:52.930
and use that to enhance
your cognitive focus

01:59:52.930 --> 01:59:55.390
for things that have
nothing to do with exercise.

01:59:55.390 --> 01:59:56.620
So this might be writing, or reading,

01:59:56.620 --> 01:59:58.750
or music, or math, et cetera.

